definition.value: The (R)-enantiomer of 2-hydroxyglutaric acid.
An octadeca-9,11-dienoic acid having 9-cis,11-trans-stereochemistry.
An ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of tyramine; major species at pH 7.3.
A 4-hydroxymandelic acid that has S-configuration.
A 4-hydroxymandelic acid that has R-configuration.
A 2-hydroxycarboxylate that is obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 4-hydroxymandelic acid.
The cis-isomer of aconitic acid.
The trans-isomer of aconitic acid.
A dihydroxybenzoic acid that is 2,4-dihydroxybenzoic acid in which the hydrogen at position 6 is replaced by a methyl group.
An oxo dicarboxylic acid that is (Z)-2-hexenedioic acid in which the hydrogens at position 5 are substituted by an oxo group.
An amino dicarboxylic acid that is L-glutamic acid substituted by a hydroxy group at position 3.
An N-acyl-L-alpha-amino acid anion resulting from deprotonation of both carboxy groups and protonation of the amino group of 3-hydroxy-L-glutamic acid.
An  amino dicarboxylic acid that is L-glutamic acid substituted by a hydroxy group at position 4.
An L-alpha-amino acid anion resulting from deprotonation of the carboxy groups and protonation of the amino group of 4-hydroxy-L-glutamic acid
A dicarboxylic acid dianion obtained by deprotonation of both carboxy groups of N-amidino-L-aspartic acid.
An N-carbamoyl-L-alpha-amino acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy groups of N-carbamoyl-L-aspartic acid.
A 2-hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is the enol-form of phenylpyruvic acid, consisting of acrylic acid having a hydroxy substituent at the 2-position and a phenyl group at the 3-position.
A 2-oxo monocarboxylic acid that is the 2-keto derivative of propionic acid. It is a metabolite obtained during glycolysis.
A member of the class of cinnamamides obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-coumaric acid with the primary amino group of agmatine.
An L-alpha-amino acid anion that is the conjugate base of L-threonine, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
The L-enantiomer of threoninium.
The D-enantiomer of  allothreonine. It occurs as a component of peptido-lipids in certain bacteria.
The D-enantiomer of threoninate.
The D-enantiomer of threoninium.
A serinate that is the conjugate base of L-serine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A serinium that is the conjugate acid of L-serine, obtained by protonation of the amino group.
The univalent carboacyl group formed by loss of -OH from the carboxy group of L-serine.
The D-enantiomer of serinate.
The D-enantiomer of serinium.
